  "prompt": "What is the climate of California's coastal regions, and how does it compare to the climate in Missouri?",
  "response": "California's coastal regions generally experience a Mediterranean climate, characterized by mild, wet winters and dry, warm summers. The temperature is moderated by the Pacific Ocean, resulting in cooler summers and warmer winters compared to inland areas. The average temperature along the coast ranges from the mid-50s\u00b0F (13\u00b0C) in winter to the mid-70s\u00b0F (24\u00b0C) in summer. Coastal areas also receive more precipitation than inland regions, with annual rainfall ranging from 10 to 30 inches (250 to 760 mm).\n\nIn contrast, Missouri has a humid subtropical climate in the southern part and a humid continental climate in the northern part. This means Missouri experiences hot, humid summers and cold winters with more variable precipitation throughout the year. The average temperature in Missouri ranges from the low 30s\u00b0F (-1\u00b0C) in winter to the mid-80s\u00b0F (29\u00b0C) in summer. Missouri typically receives more rainfall annually than California's coastal regions, with an average of 35 to 50 inches (890 to 1270 mm).\n\nIn summary, California's coastal regions have a milder and more stable climate with less rainfall compared to Missouri, which experiences more extreme temperatures and higher precipitation throughout the year.",
